 England, United Kingdom","Upton Pyne, Devon, England":"Upton Pyne, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Pyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (north-West Midlands, Lancashire, Yorkshire, and Norfolk): nickname from Middle English (Old French) <i>pie</i> ‘magpie’, which could be given to someone who wore black and white clothing, had grey-streaked dark hair, or had a loud, chattering voice and impertinent behaviour, or was cunning or sly. The uncomplimentary senses derive from the bird's behavior and are recorded uses of the word in Middle English and early Modern English.","English: occasionally perhaps a topographic or habitational name referring to a house or inn named <i>Pie</i> ‘magpie’. There were two London taverns so named, but whether these gave rise to a hereditary surname is not known. Surnames derived from house and inn signs are rare in English.","English (of Norman origin): nickname from Anglo-Norman French and Middle English <i>pie</i> ‘merciful, compassionate, kind’, a variant of Old French, Anglo-Norman French <i>piu</i>, <i>peu</i>; see   Pew   (2)."],"variants":[{"name":"Pew","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Pugh  .","English: nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>pi(u)</i>, <i>piw</i>, <i>peu</i> ‘holy, pious’, also ‘merciful, kind, compassionate’."]},{"name":"Pyatt","meanings":["English (mainly Staffordshire): nickname either from Middle English <i>piot</i> ‘magpie’ (Old French <i>pïot</i>, a diminutive of Old French <i>pie</i>), commonly used to denote a chattering woman, or alternatively from an unrecorded Middle English <i>pyard</i>, an uncomplimentary term derived from the same Old French word + <i>-(h)ard</i>. Compare   Pye  .","Variant of   Piatt  , a surname of French and Walloon origin.","History: This surname (see 2 above) is listed along with the variant <i>Piatt</i> in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."]},{"name":"Pie","meanings":["English: variant of   Pye  , in part a cognate of 2 below.","French: nickname from Old French <i>pie</i> ‘magpie’, perhaps given to a talkative person or someone who had a loud, chattering voice.","French (<b>Pié</b>): variant of   Piet   ‘foot’. Compare   Pease   and   Pee  ."]}]},{"name":"Simon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."],"variants":[{"name":"Simen","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Simon de Pyn was born about 1122, in Devon, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Simon de Pyn."},"et":{"about 1122–":"umbes 1122–Surnud","1120–1166":"1120–1